diamonds%>%ggplot(aes(carat,cut))+geom_boxplot()

Carat is the best predictor of the price of each diamond, the correlation between carat and cut is when cut is worse, carat tends to have higher median values. So with diamonds with low quality, the higher carat amount will bid up the price. ## Exercise 4

By using the density function, we could visulize the carat distribution in different price intervals represented by different colors of the curve. ## Exercise 3

diamonds%>%filter(carat<1)%>%ggplot(aes(price,carat))+geom_point(alpha=0.1)

diamonds%>%filter(carat>=1)%>%ggplot(aes(price,carat))+geom_point(alpha=0.1)

When the carat amount is lower than one(smaller diamond), it tends to have a stronger positive relationship with price and size and the slope is bigger. As carat amount is larger than 1, the slope tends to be smaller and the positive relationship tends to be weaker as the standard deviation is larger.
